**[F-020-01]** The simplification-mode checklist (ordered safe operations + behavior-preservation contract) is the strongest net-new candidate. `sk-code-review/references/removal_plan.md` identifies WHAT to remove but not HOW to simplify safely. An ADAPT as a lightweight `assets/opencode/checklists/simplification_mode.md` â€” loaded as an optional overlay when `sk-code` intent is `CODE_QUALITY` + `REMOVAL` â€” would fill a real gap without adding agents. Effort: S.

**[F-020-02]** The a11y audit schedule (initial load â†’ major UI change â†’ final verification) is a concrete quality gate improvement. `sk-code` requires browser evidence but does not structure WHEN a11y audits should fire. An ADAPT adding a one-line a11y audit trigger to `sk-code`'s WEBFLOW verification section (`SKILL.md:236`) would be sufficient. Iteration 012's "accessibility_snapshot over screenshots" finding (`iteration-012.md:14`) supports this.

**[F-020-03]** 17 of 20 sub-features are REJECT because spec-kit already covers them (7) or because they are infrastructure/deployment concerns outside spec-kit's scope (10). Spec-kit is deliberately a spec + workflow + review framework, not a deployment pipeline or E2E test runner. The DEPLOYMENT intent in `sk-code`'s `INTENT_SIGNALS` (`references/smart_routing.md:45`) exists as a keyword hook but intentionally has no `RESOURCE_MAP` entry â€” the gap is by design, not oversight.

**[F-020-04]** The console-error + network-failure capture item is a marginal ADAPT. Console errors are already required by `sk-code/SKILL.md:191`. Adding explicit network-failure capture (â‰Ą400 status) as a one-line addition to the WEBFLOW verification contract would close the gap at negligible cost. The `mcp-chrome-devtools` scripts already capture HAR traces that include network failures â€” the gap is in the verbal contract, not the tooling.

### NEGATIVE / RULED-OUT
- Adding gem-code-simplifier, gem-browser-tester, or gem-devops as new agents: REJECT. The spec-kit's `@review` + `sk-code` + `sk-code-review` baseline+surface-evidence model already handles code quality, browser evidence, and review. New agents would fragment the skill routing surface.
- Deploy approval gates in spec-kit: REJECT. Spec-kit governs specs and code quality, not deployment pipelines. Approval gates belong in CI/CD tooling (GitHub Actions, etc.).
- Docker/K8s/container best practices: REJECT. Out of scope for a spec+workflow framework.
- Feature flag lifecycle adoption from gem-devops: REJECT. Spec-kit already has its own feature-flag governance (`249-feature-flag-governance.md`) with sunset audits. Gem's canary-rollout model is for application feature flags, a different domain.

